<ol class="references">
<li id="cite_note-0"><b><a href="#cite_ref-0" title="">^</a></b> The word <a href="/wiki/British_threepence_coin" title="British threepence coin" class="mw-redirect">"threepenny"</a> refers to a coin in Britain's pre-decimal currency; the musical's title in its English-language translation reflects the common pronunciation of that coin ("THREP-penny"). The coin was discontinued in 1971 after the decimalization of sterling.</li>
<li id="cite_note-1"><b><a href="#cite_ref-1" title="">^</a></b> In an acknowledgement of the earlier work, Weill sets his opening number, <i>Morgenchoral des Peachum</i>, to the music used by composer <a href="/wiki/Johann_Christoph_Pepusch" title="Johann Christoph Pepusch">Pepusch</a> in Gay's original.</li>
